@node Install
II.  Installation

   Just execute the install program named "Install".  This
will copy the required fonts from the "Questions2.1" directory
to your FONTS: directory.
   You must also add the following somewhere in your
user-startup routine:

    assign Questions2.1: <directory>/Questions2.1

Of course, <directory> is where you unpacked (or
moved) the files.











@endnode
@node What
III.  What is Questions 2.1?

   FREEWARE-I know that was bothering your conscious, so I
got it over with as quickly as possible.  You don't owe a thing for
it.  How could I ask you for money when I can't pay the one's
who created much better programs.  So if you do feel generous,
send your donations to authors of such programs as FreePaint,
@{"ACE" link Ack 5}, and DICE. These have helped many broke Amiga users make
the most out of their machines-especially in the States where an
Amiga owner is as common as necrophilia.

   The program is a flashcard simulator to help one study.
It has all the features of handwritten flashcards.  For instance,
one can @{"randomize" link Use 11} the order of the cards or @{"flip" link Use 14} them over and view
the answer and respond with the question.  It is very helpful to
me for classes which require blind memorization since I don't
like studying for classes like that, but I do like using the Amiga.











@endnode
@node Start
IV.  Starting the Program

   After you have made a test there are two ways to begin
it:
      Workbench:  Double-click on the "Questions" icon.
				 or
		  Click on the test icon, hold down
		  shift, then double-click on the
		  "Questions" icon.

      CLI:     Type (in the "Questions2.1:" @{"directory" link Install 6}:
		  Questions [TestFilename]

   To copy my icon to your test, go to the CLI (shell) and type
the following:

   cd Questions2.1:Tests/examples
   copy example.txt.info to <TestFileName>.info

   Of course, be sure to have "Questions2.1:" @{"assigned" link Install 6} to the
directory where you installed the package.










@endnode
@node Make
V.  Making a Test

   I wanted to make an editor that was easily manipulated
for all users; therefore, I didn't make one at all.  Instead, I
decided to let you use your own favorite text editor @{"(for now)" link Future 2}.
I prefer "ED" which came with my Amiga from Commodore due to its
simplicity.  You may prefer to use your word processor
because of the advantages of spell-checking.  "Questions"
really doesn't care (see next paragraph).

   What it does care about, though, is that the test is in
ASCII.	Text editors such as ED that came with the Amiga already
write in the ASCII format with no imbedded commands, but most
word processors usually do not.  There should be an option,
however, in your word processor to export the file as ASCII.  Be
sure to do so.

   Also, DO NOT ALLOW WORD-WRAPPING!  This can be
accomplished by extending your right margin way out in your
word processor, or using a text editor that does not care how
long a row of text is.	"Questions" will do the word
wrapping for you later.

   The reason for no word-wrapping when entering the text
is that "Questions" takes each line as a separate entry.  The
first entry (line) is the first question, the second entry (line) is
the first answer, the third entry (line) is the second question, the
fourth entry (line) is the second answer...etc.  Here is an
example:

    How old are you?
    23
    What year were you born?
    1972
    What is your girlfriend's name?
    Rosie Palm

   As you can see word-wrapping would cause the wrapped
part of the line to become the answer to the first part of the line.
So, don't let this happen!!!  Look at the files in the "Tests"
directory to see how a test may be written if you still don't
understand.

   It is okay, however, to put a row of nothing between each
question and/or answer.  The program will ignore any empty
lines (which consist of just a hard return).  Here is an example
of what I mean:

    How old are you?
    21

    What year were you born?
    1972

    What is your girlfriend's name?
    Rosie Palm

   This would be perfectly acceptable. Remember:  the
only thing not acceptable is for a continuous line to be
@{"word-wrapped" link Make 23} by the text editor or word processor!!!!

   A new feature to 2.1 is the ability to enter pronunciations.
This is helpful if you are making tests that the Amiga translator
does not @{"pronounce" link Use 22} correctly.  To make a test with pronunciations,
the keyword "pronounce" must be the first line of the text file.
You then must follow a line with its pronunciation (empty lines are
still allowed) for EVERY question and answer.  Here's an example:

    pronounce

    What is Sean's last name?
    Wut is Shawnz last naym?

    Miller
    Miller











@endnode
@node Use
VI.  Using the Program

   The program is pretty straight forward.  Here are the
definitions of the buttons:

   BEGIN       - Starts the testing of a loaded test.
		 The timer begins immediately after
		 pressing this.

   NEW	       - Let's you load a new test to take.

   RANDOM      - Scrambles the order of the questions
		 and answers.

   REVERSE     - Gives the answer and asks for
		 the question.	Just like Jeopardy!

   CONFIG      - This stores your current button
		 settings to the file under the
		 directory "ConfigFiles" called
		 "Questions.cfg".

   SPEECH      - This will ask you if you want to
		 see the questions as well as have
		 the computer speak them.  Not seeing
		 them would be good for learning to
		 spell.  See the @{"previous section" link Make 61} on
		 how to enter a test with pronunciations
		 if the Amiga translator is slaughtering
		 your words when speaking them.

   RESPONSE    - This will have the computer play sound
		 @{"samples" link Samp} randomly after you answer
		 a question.  You can add up to 80
		 samples total of your own!  Its nice
		 to have feedback.

   PRINT       - Copies the file straight from the
		 drive to your printer allowing you
		 to continue while it's printing.

   EDIT        - This will invoke the program "ED"
		 with the test.  You must press
		 Amiga M to switch back to the
		 workbench screen to edit.  Note:
		 edits do NOT update in "Questions"
		 until the test is loaded again.
		 See @{"Future Versions" link Future} on this.

   <---        - These are to flip back and forth
   ---> 	 through the deck to look at previously
		 answered questions.  Note:  your @{"timer" link Use 5}
		 is still going as it should!

   QUIT        - This does diffent things at different
		 parts of the program.	Just keep clicking
		 it to fully exit the program.	During
		 a test, it will just stop the test and
		 tally up your score to the point where
		 you stopped.  When flipping back through
		 the deck with the above mentioned buttons,
		 it will take you back to where you left off
		 before flipping back through the deck.

   Others      - A string gadget where you can type in the
		 the name of a test to @{"load" link use 9} it.

	       - Two slider gadgets to quickly select your
		 starting and stopping questions.

	       - Two integer gadgets to enter in manually
		 the starting and stopping questions.











@endnode
@node Samp
VII.  Using Samples

   @{"Samples" link Use 31} are used so that the computer will give a response
when you either answer the question correctly or incorrectly.
Responses add a little fun to the program.  I was afraid
of users getting bored with them, so I made it flexible.  To
add your own responses you must edit the following files in
the "Questions2.1" @{"directory" link Install 6}:

      ConfigFiles/RightIffs
      ConfigFiles/Wrongiffs

   These files must hold the complete pathname of an
IFF sampled sound.  Place only one pathname per line.  The
LIMIT IS FORTY SAMPLES per file.  I have included some of my
favorites to help you get started.
   Remember:  if you move my favorite samples to another
directory, you MUST change the path name in the appropiate
file!  See Future Versions for more on this.











@endnode
@node Future
VIII.  Future Versions

   I may break down and make an editor which works with
the main program.  At first I didn't like the idea because
people hate to learn a different editor than their favorite.
The benefit, however, is not having to @{"reload" link Use 41} the test after
editing it.

   I would like to make it so one could easily add and delete
@{"samples" link Samp} via a nice GUI.  This is first on my list of reworks;
however, I'm sure to be sidetracked by a new project as usual
and it may be a while for the next release.

   I may ditch the crazy GUI for a more conservative Intuition
GUI.  I will only do so if I learn how to link pictures to
my gadgets rather than having to use text.  I would then
allow all options to be accessible from menus as well as
keyboard shortcuts.










@endnode
